\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0\fs28\lang9\tab\b\tab\tab Control Statements\par
\b0 Java compiler executes the code from top to bottom. The statements in the code are executed according to the order in which they appear. However, Java provides statements that can be used to control the flow of Java code. Such statements are called control flow statements.\par
They control how your program runs, based on conditions or loops.\par
Java provides three types of control flow statements.:\par
\par
\b Conditional/Decision Making statements\b0\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 if statements\par
switch statement\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Loop statements\b0\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 do while loop\par
while loop\par
for loop\par
for-each loop\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Jump statements\b0\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 break statement\par
continue statement\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Decision-Making statements:\b0\par
As the name suggests, decision-making statements decide which statement to execute and when. Decision-making statements evaluate the Boolean expression and control the program flow depending upon the result of the condition provided. There are two types of decision-making statements in Java, i.e.,\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1  1. If statement\par
 2. switch statement.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b 1) If Statement:\cf0\b0\par
\tab In Java, the "if" statement is used to evaluate a condition. \par
The condition of the If statement gives a Boolean value, either true or false. In Java, there are four types of if-statements\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 i. Simple if statement\par
ii. if-else statement\par
iii. if-else-if ladder\par
iv. Nested if-statement\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf1 i)  Simple if statement:\cf0\par
It evaluates a Boolean expression and enables the program to enter a block of code if the expression evaluates to true.\par
\b Example 1:\b0\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf1 public class Main \{\par
    public static void main(String[] args) \{\par
        int number = 10;\par
        // Simple if statement\par
        if (number >100) \{\par
            System.out.println("The number is positive.");\par
        \}\par
        System.out.println("This line always prints.");\par
    \}\par
\}\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b Example 2:\b0\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf1 import java.util.Scanner;\par
public class Main \{\par
    public static void main(String[] args) \{\par
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\par
        System.out.print("Enter your age: ");\par
        int age = scanner.nextInt();\par
         if (age >= 18) \{\par
            System.out.println("You are eligible to vote!");\par
        \}\par
        System.out.println("Thank you for checking.");\par
    \}\par
\}\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b 2) if-else statement:\cf0\b0\par
The if-else statement is an extension to the if-statement, which uses another block of code, i.e., else block. The else block is executed if the condition of the if-block is evaluated as false.\par
\b Example 1:\cf1\b0\par

\pard\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 import java.util.Scanner;\par
public class Main \{\par
    public static void main(String[] args) \{\par
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\par
        System.out.print("Enter a number: ");\par
        int number = scanner.nextInt();\par
        // if-else statement\par
        if (number % 2 == 0) \{\par
            System.out.println("The number is even.");\par
        \} else \{\par
            System.out.println("The number is odd.");\par
        \}\par
    \}\par
\}\par

